# 📦 SUMMARY  
# These commands help you manage Jenkins containers via Docker and access the Jenkins Plugin Manager UI via web URLs.  
# Language/Platform: Bash + Web URLs  
# What you'll learn: Listing Docker containers, starting a stopped container, and accessing Jenkins' plugin interfaces  
# Outcome: Jenkins container will be running and accessible, and you can manage plugins through the browser  
# Why this matters: Jenkins plugins extend functionality (e.g., Git, Docker, Node, pipelines); managing them is a key part of CI/CD setup  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: List All Docker Containers  
# ------------------------------  
docker ps -a  
# ✅ What it does: Lists all Docker containers (running, stopped, exited, etc.)  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Useful to verify if your Jenkins container exists or is stopped  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Start Jenkins Container  
# ------------------------------  
docker start <container-id>  
# ✅ What it does: Starts a previously stopped Jenkins container  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Jenkins must be running to access the web UI and plugin manager  
# 💡 Replace `<container-id>` with actual ID or name from `docker ps -a`  

# ------------------------------  
# 🌐 SECTION TITLE: Jenkins Plugin Manager – Available Plugins  
# ------------------------------  
http://<your-server-ip>:8080/manage/pluginManager/available  
# ✅ What it does: Opens the “Available” tab in Jenkins Plugin Manager  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Lets you search for and install new plugins from the Jenkins Update Center  

# ------------------------------  
# 🌐 SECTION TITLE: Jenkins Plugin Manager – Installed Plugins  
# ------------------------------  
http://<your-server-ip>:8080/manage/pluginManager/installed  
# ✅ What it does: Opens the “Installed” tab in Jenkins Plugin Manager  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Lets you manage (update, disable, remove) plugins that are already installed  

# ------------------------------  
# ✅ NOTES / GOTCHAS / TIPS  
# ------------------------------  
# - Access these URLs from a browser on a machine that can reach `<your-server-ip>`  
# - Ensure Jenkins is running and port 8080 is open in your firewall  
# - Use the Jenkins Plugin Manager to install essentials like:
#     - **Pipeline**, **Git**, **Docker**, **Blue Ocean**, **NodeJS**, etc.  
# - If Jenkins is behind a reverse proxy or hosted on a domain, replace `<your-server-ip>` with your actual hostname or domain  
# - To update all plugins safely, visit the “Updates” tab at `/manage/pluginManager/updates`
